        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This setup uses the maximum available sensitivity of a wide-band 3mm continuum setup.

Sensitivity

This proposal argues that in order to obtain a meaningful constraint on the YSO radio flare rate of the Orion protostars, an on-source time of about 4h with an overall 3sigma sensitivity of 20muJy is required (see text). Within this time, we expect as many as 16 flares, mainly due to the sensitivity increase over previous observations. While this sensitivity will not quite be reached when pointing at the bright Orion Nebula (because of increased system temperature in spite of spatial filtering), even the radio source population that is already known (and that will be detected at high S/N) is large enough to provide a measurement of the flare rate.

Angular resolution

This proposal targets the embedded radio point source population in the Orion BN/KL region. We need to use spatial filtering to limit the impact of the bright Orion Nebula, and we thus request to carry out these observations with the C34-7 configuration. This will result in subarcsecond resolution which is an excellent match to the resolution of the deep Chandra Orion data and our previously obtained JVLA data. At the same time, this configuration ensures maximum spatial filtering of extended structure.

Scheduling

While the total time of 7.8h should ideally be scheduled as a single observation (the source visibility above an elevation of 20 deg is about 9h), these observations can also be scheduled as non-contiguous runs.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
