    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to carry out the first systematic survey to determine the millimeter-wavelength flare rate of young stellar objects (YSOs), enabled by the unprecedented sensitivity of ALMA. While the X-ray flare rate of YSOs is now well constrained, only very few radio flares toward YSOs have been observed so far. An understanding of high-energy processes in YSOs and their impact on protoplanetary disks will require good knowledge of both. Compared to the cm radio range, ALMA will provide access to emission from electrons at even higher energies. First estimates indicate that the YSO radio flare rate is substantial. Establishing this number will also help assess its impact on the constant-flux assumption in synthesis imaging, limiting the available dynamic range in observations of any young cluster. The Orion Nebula Cluster is an ideal target for measuring the YSO radio flare rate because 1) many well-studied, radio-bright YSOs are accessible with a single pointing, and 2) most (of a few) published examples of spectacular YSO radio (incl. mm) flares were found here. Finally, these short ALMA observations would leverage our extensive recent JVLA observations at different cm wavelengths.</prp:abstract>
